    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:08788a0f-bb46-42a3-8b7d-9edef714f655",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 53-year-old woman who appears mildly uncomfortable when moving from sitting to standing and often shifts position to relieve stiffness in her lower back. She is overweight, neatly dressed, and otherwise well groomed. During conversation she occasionally places a hand over her lumbosacral area and describes a dull, aching pain across the lower back with intermittent muscle tightness, worse after prolonged sitting, housework, and long drives. She says the pain is sometimes associated with tenderness to touch over the lower lumbar area and at times shoots from the low back into the right buttock and down the back of the thigh to about the calf, especially after sitting too long, consistent with mild sciatica. She denies bowel or bladder incontinence and does not report saddle anesthesia.\n\nShe works as an office administrator for a regional insurance company, spending most of the day at a computer. Her commute is about 40 minutes each way, and she notes that sitting for long periods aggravates her symptoms. At home, she helps care for her elderly mother and often performs lifting and bending tasks that seem to trigger flares. She enjoys gardening, light cooking, and walking with a neighbor, though she has become less active over the past year because of fear of worsening the pain. She admits feeling increasingly anxious about whether the pain will become chronic or interfere with her ability to work and care for her family.\n\n{patientName} lives with her spouse and maintains close contact with two adult children who live nearby. She describes herself as dependable and busy, often putting family responsibilities before her own health. Sleep has been somewhat disrupted because turning in bed can provoke discomfort. She is frustrated by the persistence of the pain but remains functional and independent in activities of daily living.\n\nHer diet is mixed, with frequent convenience meals during busy workweeks, and she drinks 1-2 cups of coffee daily. She does not use illicit drugs and drinks alcohol only socially. She is a former smoker who quit years ago. She has recently tried using a heating pad and over-the-counter analgesics with partial relief, and she is interested in strategies that would let her stay active without worsening symptoms."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c641bd8e-7105-48a2-b090-482f0581a7a1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of hypertension and seasonal allergic rhinitis. She has not had prior spinal surgery and has never been hospitalized for back problems, though she recalls several self-limited episodes of low back strain over the past 10 years, usually after heavy lifting or prolonged yard work. The current episode began gradually several weeks ago and became more noticeable after a weekend of cleaning and moving storage boxes.\n\nShe reports no history of malignancy, inflammatory arthritis, chronic corticosteroid use, or recent significant trauma. There is no known history of osteoporosis diagnosis, although she is postmenopausal. She denies fevers, chills, unintentional weight loss, marked lower-extremity weakness, urinary retention, or fecal incontinence. She does note intermittent aching and pulling pain into the right buttock and posterior leg, along with localized lumbar tenderness. Over-the-counter ibuprofen and local heat provide partial relief. Because of her persistent symptoms, she has become somewhat anxious and more hesitant to exercise.\n\nLifestyle factors include long sedentary work hours, limited core-strengthening exercise, and frequent caregiving-related lifting. She is a former smoker with an approximately 10 pack-year history, having quit in her early 40s. She drinks wine socially, about 1-2 glasses on weekends. Her functional status remains independent, but she has reduced recreational walking and gardening because of pain flare-ups.\n\nHer mother has a history of chronic low back pain related to degenerative spine disease, and {patientName} says back problems 'run in the family.' She also recently completed a short prednisone taper prescribed at an urgent care visit for a respiratory illness; while not a typical direct cause of mechanical back pain, intermittent corticosteroid exposure may contribute to bone and musculoskeletal vulnerability over time, especially in a postmenopausal patient."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
